Margaret M. Alkek 


StoryComments





        Print
    


            Create a hardcopy of this page
        


        Font Size:
    


            Default font size
        



            Larger font size
        















        Posted: Friday, April 1, 2005 12:00 am


Margaret M. Alkek

                        0 comments
                    





Margaret M. Alkek, an acclaimed philanthropist and arts patron
whose generosity of spirit set the tone for charitable giving in
Houston and across the state, passed away peacefully in the
presence of family and friends on Thursday afternoon, the March 24,
2005.


The daughter of Charles and Letyr Knight McFarland, she was born
on Feb. 23, 1916, in Houston and graduated from San Jacinto High
School in 1933. She attended the University of Texas at Austin,
where dashing young oilman Albert B. Alkek of Victoria courted her
by swooping his airplane low over her dormitory, to the delight of
her classmates. By 1934, Margaret and Albert Alkek were
married.










From the earliest days of their 61-year marriage, Mrs. Alkek
worked side by side with her husband to build a successful
business. He made the deals and she kept the company's books and
inventory. The couple later diversified their business interests
and established residences in both Bandera and Houston.
Mrs. Alkek brought to her marriage a solid appreciation for
family life and public service. She was a member of a number of
genealogical lineage societies and keenly appreciated her own
family's history and that of her hometown and state. She also
enjoyed reading, dancing, and visiting with friends. Education was
important to Mrs. Alkek, who returned to college in the late 1940's
and graduated with honors from Victoria College in 1951.
Even as a young wife and mother in Victoria, she was active in
the League of Women Voters and a member of the "Pink Ladies," the
Hospital Auxiliary for Victoria's Citizens Memorial Hospital. She
began this work with her mother and continued volunteering with her
daughter, Margaret Alkek Williams.
This community service was complemented by generous
contributions. The Alkeks shared their financial success with the
philanthropic world, giving more than $50 million to programs that
advanced medicine and education. At Mr. Alkek's death in 1995, Mrs.
Alkek became chairman of the newly formed Albert and Margaret Alkek
Foundation.
Mrs. Alkek devoted her time and resources to many nonprofit
organizations that were close to her heart. The Houston Ballet
Foundation, Houston Grand Opera, the Museum of Fine Arts, Houston,
and the Moores School of Music at the University of Houston were
among the arts programs she favored. Educational and community
programs included Delta Delta Delta, the Kronkosky Library of
Bandera County, the University of Houston System, and St.
Christopher's Episcopal Church in Bandera. Mrs. Alkek established
scholarships at Texas State University-San Marcos, the University
of Houston-Victoria, Northwood University, and the Texas Military
Institute. She also was a tremendous advocate for medical programs
such as the Cancer League, the Crohn's & Colitis Foundation of
America, the University of Texas Health Science Center at Houston,
and the University of Texas M.D. Anderson Cancer Center, home of
the Albert B. and Margaret M. Alkek Hospital.
At Baylor College of Medicine, the Margaret M. and Albert B.
Alkek Building for the Graduate School of Biomedical Sciences, the
Alkek Tower, the Alkek Fountain, the Alkek Eye Center, the Margaret
M. and Albert B. Alkek Department of Medicine, and the Margaret M.
Alkek Distinguished Chair in Medicine honor Mrs. Alkek's
philanthropic vision.
As chairman of the board of the Albert and Margaret Alkek
Foundation, Mrs. Alkek personally oversaw the strategic investment
of more than $70 million in medical, educational, and cultural
programs, including a landmark $31.25 million to Baylor College of
Medicine in 1998. "It's thrilling to wake up and be able to do
something and be productive by helping in as many ways as you
possibly can," Mrs. Alkek said at the announcement of the Baylor
gift.
Over the years, Mrs. Alkek continued to be involved in her
community. Her friends admired her gracious enthusiasm for helping
others and her energetic support of their fundraising efforts as
well as her own. One of the greatest joys in her life was her
friends.
A long-standing member of the Episcopal Church, Mrs. Alkek
attended St. John The Divine in Houston and St. Christopher's in
Bandera.
Mrs. Alkek received many honors, including a 1996 Honorary
Doctor of Philosophy Degree from St. Mary's University. The
Huffington Center on Aging at Baylor College of Medicine recognized
her service on its board with the Spirit of Anne Morrow Lindbergh
Award in 1998. In 1999, Northwood University presented her its
Distinguished Women's Award. In 2000, she received the Maurice
Hirsch Award for Philanthropy from the National Society of Fund
Raising Executives. She received the first Women of Achievement
Award at the 2000 National Convention of Delta Delta Delta in
Washington, D.C.
Mrs. Alkek is survived by her daughter, Margaret Alkek Williams;
her grandson, Charles A. Williams, and his wife, Randa Duncan
Williams; and her great-grandson Harrison M. Williams; all of whom
will keep her name and kindness alive in perpetuity through the
family's commitment to help others.
Friends are cordially invited to a visitation with the family
from six until eight o'clock in the evening on Wednesday, March 30,
in the foyer and library of Geo. H. Lewis & Sons, 1010 Bering
Drive in Houston.
The funeral service will be conducted at two o'clock in the
afternoon on Thursday, March 31, in the Sanctuary of St. Luke's
United Methodist Church, 3471 Westheimer Road in Houston, with the
Rev. Laurens A. Hall of St. John The Divine Episcopal Church
officiating. Honored to serve as pallbearers include Dr. Bobby R.
Alford, James L. Daniel, Dan L. Duncan, Kenneth W. Hicks, Dr. Dan
B. Jones, Michael R. McDonald, Joseph H. Peck, Jr., and Scott B.
Seaman.
Immediately following the service, the family will attend a
private committal service at Memorial Oaks Cemetery in Houston.
For those who so desire, and because of the family's involvement
with a variety of organizations, memorials in Mrs. Alkek's name may
be directed to the charity of one's choice.
Arrangements in Houston are under the direction of Geo. H. Lewis
& Sons, 1010 Bering Drive, Houston, Texas, 77057,
713.789.3005.
 


 
















