Texas Medical Center Legacy Makers – The Alkek Foundation and Alkek Family


(L-R) Margaret Alkek Williams and Charles and Randa Williams were among the family honorees at the November 2013 Crystal Ball benefiting the Huffington Center on Aging at Baylor College of Medicine. photo by kim coffman
Forty years of support and funding to Baylor College of Medicine
When Albert B. Alkek passed away in 1995, The New York Times published an article describing him as an oilman and philanthropist whose $77 million donation helped expand the nation’s largest hospital complex. He was 85 years old. The family of “Mr. A”, as he was often called, continues this legacy of giving through the Albert and Margaret Alkek Foundation.
After four decades of charitable giving, the Alkek family continues to make an impact on the Texas Medical Center (TMC). Transformational gifts — beginning with Alkek’s donation of $25 million to Baylor College of Medicine (BCM) in 1988 and $30 million to MD Anderson in 1993 for the construction of the Albert B. and Margaret M. Alkek Hospital — have changed the face of philanthropy in the TMC and improved the lives of many.
In May of this year, Baylor College of Medicine recognized the Alkek Family’s 40 years of support and more than $100 million in grant funding. Funding by the Albert and Margaret Alkek Foundation has helped to establish BCM’s leading clinical programs in medicine and ophthalmology and to fund novel research centers focused on metagenomics and microbiome research and molecular discovery.
Yet BCM is only one of hundreds of institutions and nonprofits that have been blessed by the Alkek Foundation and family, and today, the next generations are carrying on the legacy.
Early Years 
Albert B. Alkek was born in Houston in 1909. Soon after his birth, the family moved to Victoria, where they were prominent in the ranching and grocery trades.
Alkek attended Victoria public schools and later transferred to Peacock Military Academy in San Antonio. He attended St. Mary’s University, but withdrew before completing his degree. Nevertheless, Alkek went on to have incredible success in the oil industry and in 1987, Forbes magazine estimated his net worth at $310 million.
During World War II, Alkek met his mentor, Harry F. Sinclair, founder and owner of Sinclair Oil Corp., and in 1942, he invited Sinclair to dinner. This gesture was the beginning of a partnership, which six years later led to the formation of the Sinclair-Alkek Oil Co. which built and operated the first products pipeline in Texas. In 1952, Sinclair sold his interest to Alkek, who continued to operate the company as the Alkek Oil Company.
At various points in his career, Alkek was the largest independent gasoline supplier in the state of Texas and the Southwest, and at one time was one of the most active individual traders on Wall Street, trading at an annual volume of $75 million in 1965.
Health and education were always important interests and, over time, Alkek began making large gifts to medical and educational institutions that reached out to him for support. In 1977, he became a trustee of BCM where he served 17 years. He served on the board of many other public and private companies and charitable institutions and received numerous awards and honors.
According to Scott Seaman, Executive Director of the Albert and Margaret Alkek Foundation, personal relationships were key to Alkek’s philanthropic philosophy. His friendship with the world-renowned Dr. Michael DeBakey led to his involvement with BCM and other institutions in the Texas Medical Center.
Noted Seaman, “Mr. Alkek was an astute businessman, and had an incredible memory; his mind was like an internal computer. He could run numbers in his head. Those fortunate enough to have met him, would remember his charismatic personality. I admired him for being a man of clear vision and determination. With decades of experience in personal philanthropy, he knew exactly how he wanted to establish his legacy.”
Margaret M. Alkek
Margaret M. Alkek, an acclaimed philanthropist and arts patron whose generosity of spirit set the tone for charitable giving in Houston, passed away March 24, 2005. “Mrs. Alkek was very gracious and thoughtful. She remembered personal details about people, and was incredibly kind,” Seaman said.
Mrs. Alkek was born Feb. 23, 1916, in Houston. She attended the University of Texas in Austin, where the dashing young oilman, Albert B. Alkek, courted her — to the delight of her classmates — by swooping his airplane low over her dormitory. By 1934, the couple was married.
From the earliest days of their 61-year marriage, Mrs. Alkek worked with her husband to build a successful business. He made the deals and she kept the books. The couple later diversified their business interests and established residences in both Bandera and Houston.
Mrs. Alkek had a solid appreciation for family life and public service. Even as a young wife and mother, she was active in numerous organizations and societies. Her community service was complemented by her generous contributions. With Alkek’s death in 1995, Mrs. Alkek became chairman of the newly formed Albert and Margaret Alkek Foundation.
Mrs. Alkek devoted her time and resources to many nonprofit organizations close to her heart, which included Houston’s arts community, libraries, churches, numerous educational institutions, and the medical community.
“My mother and I were always very close, but after my father passed away we grew even more connected. She lost my father, but never lost her drive to be of service to her community,” said her daughter, Margaret Alkek Williams.
 
Albert and Margaret Alkek Foundation
“The Foundation was started by my grandfather,” said Charles Williams, President of the Albert and Margaret Alkek Foundation. “It was created by his will and was a direct result of his life as a businessman. He was a wildcatter, a stock trader and an entrepreneur, but he started out with nothing.”
He continued, “In 1988, when he donated $25 million to BCM, it was the largest individual charitable donation that had ever been made to the Texas Medical Center. It was also the first time one of his donations had received media coverage. My grandfather saw the impact it had and this donation became a springboard with regard to his charitable giving. Up until that point, he had been very private.”
To implement his philanthropic vision, Alkek selected 11 executors of his will to serve as the Foundation’s original directors. “Mr. Alkek charged us with establishing the Albert and Margaret Alkek.
Dr. Paul Klotman, president of Baylor College of Medicine, honors Margaret Alkek Williams for her family’s support of BCM.







Comments are closed.





